  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and in the workshops I've attended with other skilled tradespeople. When you're a carpenter who's spent decades learning the craft, you know that your hands and your mind are your tools. But when you're told that 'STEM is for the smart ones' or 'you're not cut out for engineering,' that message can make you doubt yourself even when you know you're capable. I remember when I was younger, my father, who has a PhD, would say, 'Don't let anyone tell you you can't do it.' But now, with the way schools and workplaces talk about STEM, it's easy to feel like you're not measuring up. Stereotype threat isn't about being bad at math—it's about the fear that your identity might hold you back. We need to address this by creating environments where people feel safe to try, fail, and learn without judgment. For example, in my community, we've started hosting hands-on workshops where carpenters and engineers work together on building projects. This helps break down the barriers and shows that skills aren't divided by trade or discipline. It's not about changing the system overnight; it's about small, practical steps that build confidence and show that everyone has a place in STEM.",
